[1] Japan: travel alert
Date: Mon 21 Aug 2017
Source: The Mainichi [edited]
https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20170821/p2g/00m/0dm/077000c


Japan's health ministry has issued a warning for people traveling to Europe on the back of an outbreak of measles in countries such as Italy and Romania. The Ministry of Health, Labor and Welfare is advising tourists to go to hospital if they develop a high fever or generalized rash after returning to Japan.

Although the World Health Organization verified that Japan has eliminated infections of endemic measles strains in 2015, group infections originating from people who contracted the disease abroad are spreading in the country. As of [6 Aug 2017], the number of patients reached 169 this year in Japan, already eclipsing the figure in the previous year.

About 4100 patients in Italy and around 6500 patients in Romania have already been confirmed as of August [2017] compared with about 860 and 2000, respectively, throughout 2016, according to the European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control.

Symptoms of the highly contagious disease include runny nose, red and watery eyes, high fever, and rash. The virus is spread through coughing and sneezing and can cause complications such as pneumonia and can even result in death in one in 1000 patients, according to the ministry. The ministry recommends people traveling overseas to check their vaccination records and take an additional shot if they have only been vaccinated once.

The disease was prevalent about a decade ago in Japan with the number of patients soaring to over 10 000 in 2008 but the country was later considered as free from infections of the virus.

